<paragraph blockId="108.[189,1399,961,1833]" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">
Fore wing length 
<quantity box="[411,548,962,988]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="14.0">14–16 mm</quantity>
. Antenna with 53–62 flagellomeres. First flagellomere about 3.0–3.5 times as long as wide. Central flagellomeres in male usually longer than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[1140,1313,997,1023]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratus">
<emphasis box="[1140,1313,997,1023]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. obscuratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, about 1.6 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[523,623,1032,1058]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1746,1772]" captionTargetBox="[371,1220,293,1682]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[340,1247,262,1708]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. A–D. Occipital carina posterior view. A. Ophion confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). B. O. mocsaryi Brauns, 1889. C. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. D. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. E–G. Hind trochanter and trochantellus dorsal view. E. O. slaviceki Kriechbaumer, 1892. F. O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1798. G. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. H–I. Mandible ventral view. H. O. obscuratus. I. O. slaviceki. J–K. First tergite, aberration O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. J. Dorsal view. K. Lateral view. L–M. Head in posterior view showing generalized shape of occipital carina. L. O. obscuratus. M. O. variegatus Rudow, 1883. N–O. Central flagellomeres in males. N. O. obscuratus. O. O. variegatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476416/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 7O</figureCitation>
). Subapical flagellomeres approximately 1.5–1.6 times as long as wide. Temples slightly buccate. Head in lateral view temple 0.7–0.8 times as long as compound eye in females and 0.5–0.6 times in males. Face wide in anterior view (
<figureCitation box="[1096,1212,1102,1129]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[189,232,1881,1907]" captionTargetBox="[270,1318,265,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[270,1318,265,1837]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 17. Head, anterior view. A. Ophion variegatus Rudow, 1883, female. B. O. sylvestris Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008721). C. O. perkinsi Brock, 1982, ♂. D. O. norei Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♂ (NHRS-HEVA000008687). E. O. perkinsi, ♀. F. O. norei Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008691)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476442/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
). Gap between compound eye and lateral ocellus usually distinct, about 0.3 times the diameter of ocellus. Occipital carina usually curved before junction with hypostomal carina, junction usually with an angle of 70–90 degrees (
<figureCitation box="[384,492,1208,1235]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1746,1772]" captionTargetBox="[371,1220,293,1682]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[340,1247,262,1708]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. A–D. Occipital carina posterior view. A. Ophion confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). B. O. mocsaryi Brauns, 1889. C. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. D. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. E–G. Hind trochanter and trochantellus dorsal view. E. O. slaviceki Kriechbaumer, 1892. F. O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1798. G. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. H–I. Mandible ventral view. H. O. obscuratus. I. O. slaviceki. J–K. First tergite, aberration O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. J. Dorsal view. K. Lateral view. L–M. Head in posterior view showing generalized shape of occipital carina. L. O. obscuratus. M. O. variegatus Rudow, 1883. N–O. Central flagellomeres in males. N. O. obscuratus. O. O. variegatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476416/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Figs 7M</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[506,562,1208,1235]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="123.[189,232,1947,1973]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,680,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@123.[189,1399,679,1905]" captionTargetPageId="123" captionText="Fig. 50. Ophion variegatus Rudow, 1883, neotype, ♀ (MNHN). A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Epicnemial carina, lateroventral view. C. Occipital carina, lateroventral view. D. Labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476516/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">50C</figureCitation>
). Malar space about 0.2 times as long as mandibular base in female and male. Mandibular gape right-angled, with internal angles. Wing membrane clear. Ramellus usually short, reaching 0.1–0.3 times the width of the discosubmarginal cell. Radius sinuous. Structure of mesopleuron shining or with distinct microsculptures between punctures, with weak, very regular punctation consisting of small punctures. Interstices between punctures about equal to their diameter, up to 2.0 times their diameter. Epicnemial carina, in antero-ventral view, with pleurosternal angles obviously anterior to sternal angles. Pleurosternal angles rounded, usually right angled, rarely obtuse or slightly acute. Sternal angles usually more distinct and the epicnemal carina between the sternal and pleurosternal angles more concave than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[1003,1173,1490,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratus">
<emphasis box="[1003,1173,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. obscuratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1190,1299,1489,1516]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="123.[189,232,1947,1973]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,680,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@123.[189,1399,679,1905]" captionTargetPageId="123" captionText="Fig. 50. Ophion variegatus Rudow, 1883, neotype, ♀ (MNHN). A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Epicnemial carina, lateroventral view. C. Occipital carina, lateroventral view. D. Labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476516" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476516/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 50B</figureCitation>
) but the overlap is considerable. Scutellum without lateral carinae. Structure of propodeum similar to that of 
<emphasis box="[189,308,1560,1587]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johansson &amp; Cederberg" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[189,305,1560,1587]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteus">O. luteus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Posterior to anterior transverse carina mostly shining. Anterior transverse carina always present centrally anterior to area superomedia, but often also present laterally, though rarely strongly raised. Posterior transverse carina usually only present laterally, widely interrupted centrally (as in 
<figureCitation box="[189,301,1666,1692]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1739,1765]" captionTargetBox="[305,1281,298,1666]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[263,1325,265,1697]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 10. Generalized carination of propodeum in females, posterodorsal view. A. Ophion luteus (Linnaeus, 1758)/O. scutellaris Thomson, 1888/O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1792. B. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. C. O. brocki Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008633). D. O. confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). E. O. crassicornis Brock, 1982. F. O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. G. O. ellenae Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008655). H. O. perkinsi Brock, 1982. I. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. J. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. K. O. dispar Brauns, 1895. L. O. tenuicornis Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008743). M. O. longigena Thomson, 1888. N. O. brevicornis Morley, 1915. O. O. forticornis Morley, 1915." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476424/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
). Central longitudinal carinae weak or absent. Sclerotised part of first sternite ending level to spiracle. Legs normal with hind femur about 6.0–7.0 times as long as wide. Hind trochantellus usually longer than in other species except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johansson &amp; Cederberg" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[713,823,1736,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteus">
<emphasis box="[713,823,1736,1763]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. luteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kriechbaumer" authorityYear="1892" box="[838,982,1736,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="slaviceki">
<emphasis box="[838,982,1736,1763]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. slaviceki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[1041,1211,1736,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratus">
<emphasis box="[1041,1211,1736,1763]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. obscuratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as in 
<figureCitation box="[1293,1382,1736,1763]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1746,1772]" captionTargetBox="[371,1220,293,1682]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[340,1247,262,1708]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 7. A–D. Occipital carina posterior view. A. Ophion confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). B. O. mocsaryi Brauns, 1889. C. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. D. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. E–G. Hind trochanter and trochantellus dorsal view. E. O. slaviceki Kriechbaumer, 1892. F. O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1798. G. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. H–I. Mandible ventral view. H. O. obscuratus. I. O. slaviceki. J–K. First tergite, aberration O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. J. Dorsal view. K. Lateral view. L–M. Head in posterior view showing generalized shape of occipital carina. L. O. obscuratus. M. O. variegatus Rudow, 1883. N–O. Central flagellomeres in males. N. O. obscuratus. O. O. variegatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476416/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 7F</figureCitation>
). Slightly shorter than wide in dorsal view. Inner spur of hind tibia long about 0.3–0.4 times as long as metatarsus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="108.[189,276,1872,1898]" box="[189,276,1872,1898]" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,276,1872,1898]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,276,1872,1898]" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Colour</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="108.[189,1399,1918,1980]" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">
Body usually more brownish than other species and with extensive whitish pattern on thorax (
<figureCitation box="[1246,1325,1918,1945]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="19.[189,232,1948,1974]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,780,1904]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[189,1398,780,1904]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Fig. 11. Head and mesosoma, lateral and dorsal view of female. A‒B. Ophion variegatus Rudow, 1883. C‒D. O. ventricosus Gravenhorst, 1829." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476428/files/figure.png" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
A–B), similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[391,556,1954,1980]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratus">
<emphasis box="[391,556,1954,1980]" italics="true" pageId="108" pageNumber="109">O. obscuratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Mandibular teeth black. Ovipositor sheath testaceous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="109.[189,358,267,293]" box="[189,358,267,293]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,358,267,293]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" reason="3">
